\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of working with the vector product, we will generalize the idea
 of projecting the parallelogram onto coordinate planes.
 Consider a parallelogram spanned by vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 in an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimen\SpecialChar \-
sion\SpecialChar \-
al Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

